> #### Author's Note: Insignificant Threat
> Some class abilities, such as a death knight's runic power, a necromancer's death knell, or a warlock's soul shards, are powered by the deaths of other creatures. In a video game, this sort of mechanic can be managed by the placement of creatures or system-based disqualification of "critter" creatures such as a rat or baby animal. However, a tabletop RPG has far too many possibilities to account for.
>
> The definition of the term insignificant threat is left to the GM's discretion, with the primary goal being to prevent metagaming or attempting to cheat the system. The creatures do not need to be a threat to the player, but their death should have some level of impact. 
>
> As an example, a warlock should not be able to gain soul shards from carrying around a bag of rats to kill for a quick power up. However, using a cage full of commoners or killing one of a number of attacking rats could be considered enough to do so. 

### Knighthood
*3rd-level death knight feature*

<div style='margin-top:-4px'></div>

You choose a path of knighthood to follow, becoming either a Knight of Blood, Knight of Frost, or Knight of the Unholy. Your choice of knighthood provides features at 3rd level and again at 7th, 10th, and 15th level.

